The AP reported in the Pittsburgh Gazette on 8/17/23: 'It cost the St Louis Americans $116 in baseballs to allow Dave Danforth to pitch against NY yesterday, as the umpires threw 58 balls out of the game. It was stated today Danforth tossed a number of balls to the umpires himself so as to avoid suspicion that he might be doctoring the ball. (NYT reported more than a dozen balls were thrown out while NY was at bat, but none was marked in such a way as to indicating 'cheating' by the local sharpshooter.)  Danforth recently was suspended for alleged tampering with a ball in a game at Philadelphia.'

The Cobb crew aroused considerable ill-feeling among spec- tators by heckling and nagging Dave Danforth. The tactics of the Detroiters resulted in a slow and tiresome ball game. A number of balls were thrown out of the game, some at Danforth's request.  (Earlier in the year, he was found to be doctoring the ball.)
The crowd cheered wildly when Jones struck out
Cobb was greeted with howls of derision when he came to bat
On the 2nd ball pitched, Rigney asked Ump Rowland to examine the pill.  The ball was put back in play after careful inspection, and Rigney fanned on the next 3 pitches.

With the count of 2-1, Rowland was again asked to examine the ball. His inspection evidently revealed a spot on the ball for he walked out to the mound and spoke a few words to Danforth, then handed him a new ball.
Play was delayed a few moments while Ump Owens went to the Browns' bench to warn them against coaching.
Danforth received another ovation when he stepped to plate
Danforth had picked Jones off 1B and run down, but Rowland reversed Owens' decision.
A light rain began while Ezzell went to bat

On his way back to the bench, Cobb picked up the ball in the pitcher's box, examined it closely, rubbed it vigorously, then tossed it over his head to Danforth.  Danforth then examined it, tossed it to Collins for another inspection before it was returned to play. The unsportsmanlike conduct of the Detroit leader roused the resentment in the stands; the crowd panned him viciously as he walked to the bench.
Cobb was again a target for a stormy uproar in the stands when he stepped to the plate.  Cobb was out on a fast play. The crowd gave way to riotous enthusiasm when the 'Georgia Peach' was called out.

Heilmann called for an inspection of the ball.  Rowland examined it, then held it out in front of him to convince Harry that Danforth had not tampered with the pill.  Rowland evidently was becoming disgusted with the poor sportsmanship of Detroit in their efforts to heckle the local slab artist. Feeble tap on the next pitch following examination of ball.
